IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDescription: PROVIDE STUDENTS WITH INTELL- ECTUAL & MORAL PREPARATION FOR RESPONSIBLE LIVING & MEANINGFUL WORK.
IRS990.MissionDescription: SHAPED BY THE CATHOLIC BENEDICTINE HERITAGE, THE COLLEGE OF ST. SCHOLASTICA PROVIDES INTELLECTUAL AND MORAL PREPARATION FOR RESPONSIBLE LIVING AND MEANINGFUL WORK. IN CONJUNCTION WITH THIS MISSION STATEMENT, THE COLLEGE'S VISION STATEMENT IS AS FOLLOWS: THE COLLEGE OF ST. SCHOLASTICA WILL BE WIDELY REGARDED AS AN ACADEMIC COMMUNITY GROUNDED IN THE RICH BENEDICTINE HERITAGE AND SENDING FORTH THOUGHTFUL LEADERS, SHARPENED AND SENSITIZED BY THE LIBERAL ARTS, WHO ARE COMMITTED TO SERVE AND TO TRANSFORM THE WORLD.
IRS990.Description: INSTRUCTION: INSTRUCTION, IN ASSOCIATION WITH THE REVENUE GENERATED FROM ITS TUITION AND FEES ASSESSED TO STUDENTS, IS THE COLLEGE'S PRIMARY TAX EXEMPT PURPOSE AND ACCOUNTS FOR OVER 80% OF THE COLLEGE'S TOTAL REVENUES. IN ADDITION TO THE MAIN CAMPUS IN DULUTH, MINNESOTA; THE COLLEGE ALSO HAS CAMPUSES IN BRAINERD, ST. CLOUD, ROCHESTER, AND ST. PAUL (ALL LOCATIONS ARE IN MINNESOTA). THE COLLEGE OFFERS A VARIETY OF MAJORS AND DEGREES INCLUDING A BACHELOR OF ARTS IN ACCOUNTING, ADVERTISING & PUBLIC RELATIONS, ART, BIOLOGY, CATHOLIC STUDIES, CHEMISTRY, COMMUNICATION, COMPUTER SCIENCE/ INFORMATION SYSTEMS, APPLIED ECONOMICS, ENGLISH, HEALTH SCIENCES, HISTORY, HUMANITIES, JOURNALISM, LANGUAGES AND INTERNATIONAL STUDIES, MANAGEMENT, MARKETING, MATHEMATICS, MUSIC, NATURAL SCIENCES, OJIBWE LANGUAGE AND CULTURE EDUCATION, ORGANIZATIONAL BEHAVIOR, PSYCHOLOGY, SOCIAL SCIENCES, SOCIAL STUDIES, SOCIAL WORK, SPANISH, THEATRE MANAGEMENT, AND THEOLOGY & RELIGIOUS STUDIES. THE COLLEGE OFFERS A BACHELOR OF SCIENCE DEGREE IN THE FOLLOWING MAJORS: BIOCHEMISTRY, CHEMISTRY, EDUCATIONAL MEDIA AND TECHNOLOGY, ELEMENTARY AND MIDDLE EDUCATION, EXERCISE PHYSIOLOGY, FINANCE, HEALTH INFORMATION MANAGEMENT, NURSING, AND PSYCHOLOGY. PRE-PROFESSIONAL PROGRAMS INCLUDE THE FIELDS OF DENTISTRY, ENGINEERING, LAW, MEDICINE, PHARMACY AND VETERINARY MEDICINE. MINORS ARE AVAILABLE IN MOST OF THE MAJOR FIELDS AS WELL AS IN AMERICAN INDIAN STUDIES, ART, FRENCH, GERMAN, GERONTOLOGY (CERTIFICATE), MEDIEVAL AND RENAISSANCE STUDIES, PHILOSOPHY, PHOTOGRAPHY, POLITICAL SCIENCE, RUSSIAN, SPANISH, THEATRE, AND WOMEN'S GENDER STUDIES. THE COLLEGE ALSO OFFERS A MASTER OF ARTS (MA) DEGREE, MASTER OF EDUCATION (M. ED.) DEGREE, MASTER OF SCIENCE (MS) DEGREE, AND A DOCTORAL DEGREE. THESE INCLUDE A MA IN ATHLETIC TRAINING, MA IN COMPUTER INFORMATION SYSTEMS, MA IN EXERCISE PHYSIOLOGY, MA IN MANAGEMENT, MBA IN MANAGEMENT, MA IN OCCUPATIONAL THERAPY, M.ED. IN CURRICULUM AND INSTRUCTION, M.ED. IN EDUCATIONAL MEDIA AND TECHNOLOGY, MS IN HEALTH INFORMATION MANAGEMENT, MS IN NURSING, MS IN TEACHING, DNP IN NURSING, AND DPT IN PHYSICAL THERAPY. DURING 2009-10, THE COLLEGE OFFERED ONLINE COURSES IN NURSING, PHYSICAL THERAPY, AND HEALTH INFORMATION MANAGEMENT.COURSE INSTRUCTION TAKES PLACE WITH THE COLLEGE'S MISSION IN MIND OF PROVIDING A STRONG LEARNING ENVIRONMENT TO PREPARE STUDENTS INTELLECTUALLY AND MORALLY FOR MEANINGFUL WORK AND RESPONSIBLE LIVING. DURING 2009-10, THE COLLEGE'S ENROLLMENT AVERAGED JUST UNDER 3,700 STUDENTS THAT CAN BE BROKEN DOWN INTO THREE MAIN GROUPS: UNDERGRADUATE TRADITIONAL, GRADUATE, AND THOSE STUDENTS ENROLLED IN THE COLLEGE'S ACCELERATED DEGREE EVENING PROGRAM. FULL-TIME EQUIVALENT (FTE) ENROLLMENT FOR THE COLLEGE WAS 3,469 AND 3,326 STUDENTS FOR FALL AND SPRING SEMESTERS, RESPECTIVELY.

Activity2.Description: STUDENT & ADMINISTRATIVE SERVICES: STUDENT SERVICES/ACADEMIC SUPPORT COVERS A BROAD RANGE OF ACTIVITIES THAT COVER ADMINISTRATION/ASSISTANCE FOR STUDENTS, ACADEMIC SUPPORT, STUDENT SUPPORT SERVICES, AND ATHLETIC/EXTRA-CURRICULAR ACTIVITIES. ADMINISTRATION/ASSISTANCE CONSISTS OF ADMISSIONS, REGISTRATION, FINANCIAL AID, AND ACADEMIC AFFAIRS. ACADEMIC SUPPORT RANGES FROM INTERPERSONAL SERVICES SUCH AS ACADEMIC ADVISEMENT AND ASSISTANCE TO FACILITIES THAT INCLUDE COMPUTER LABS/TECH SUPPORT AND THE COLLEGE'S LIBRARY. STUDENT SUPPORT SERVICES RANGE FROM ACADEMIC COUNSELING, TUTORING, CAREER COUNSELING, PERSONAL COUNSELING, GRAD SCHOOL PREPARATION, AND MENTORING. SPECIALIZED SUPPORT SERVICES ARE AVAILABLE FOR STUDENT VETERANS, STUDENTS WITH DISABILITIES, STUDENTS OF COLOR OR WHO ARE INTERNATIONAL, AND STUDENTS WHO ARE UNDERGOING RECOVERY FROM DRUG AND/OR ALCOHOL ABUSE. THE COLLEGE HAS A WIDE VARIETY OF EXTRA-CURRICULAR ACTIVITIES/SERVICES AND ATHLETIC PROGRAMS THAT AID IN PROVIDING AN ENRICHING EXPERIENCE TO OUR STUDENT POPULATION. EXTRA-CURRICULAR ACTIVITIES INCLUDE A VARIETY OF STUDENT CLUBS AND ORGANIZATIONS, CAMPUS MINISTRY, ETC., THAT PROVIDE THE MEANS FOR STUDENTS TO CONNECT AND INTERACT WITH EACH OTHER AND PROVIDING THEM AVENUES FOR PERSONAL, VOCATIONAL AND SOCIAL GROWTH. THE COLLEGE IS A MEMBER OF THE NCAA AND HAS A VARIETY OF ATHLETIC PROGRAMS FOR MALE AND FEMALE ATHLETES INCLUDING BASEBALL, SOFTBALL, BASKETBALL, CROSS-COUNTRY, FOOTBALL, ICE HOCKEY, SKIING, SOCCER, TENNIS, INDOOR/OUTDOOR TRACK, AND VOLLEYBALL. NEARLY 450 STUDENTS PARTICIPATE IN THESE PROGRAMS. FOR THOSE STUDENTS NOT IN THESE PROGRAMS, A WIDE VARIETY OF INTRAMURAL SPORT ACTIVITIES EXIST ALONG WITH GENERAL USE OF THE COLLEGE'S RECREATIONAL FACILITY, THE BURNS COMMONS WELLNESS CENTER.

Activity3.Description: AUXILIARY OPERATIONS: AUXILIARY OPERATIONS OF THE COLLEGE PROVIDE ON-CAMPUS HOUSING, FOOD SERVICE, AND HEALTH SERVICES TO THE STUDENT BODY. HOUSING CONSISTS OF THE DORMITORY SOMERS RESIDENCE HALL THAT INCLUDES A WING OF RESIDENCE HALL SUITES; AND EIGHT APARTMENT COMPLEXES: CEDAR, GROVE, BIRCH, MAPLE, PINE, WILLOW, SCANLON HALL, AND KERST HALL WITH A CAPACITY OF 1,025 BEDS. ALMOST ONE-HALF OF THE COLLEGE'S FULL-TIME UNDERGRADUATE TRADITIONAL AGED STUDENTS RESIDE ON CAMPUS. FOR 2009-10, OCCUPANCY WAS 1,058 AND 1,002 STUDENTS FOR FALL AND SPRING SEMESTERS, RESPECTIVELY. FOOD SERVICE CONSISTS OF THE GREENVIEW (DORMITORY CAFETERIA), STORM'S DEN (STUDENT UNION), AND THE JAVA EXPRESS (ALSO LOCATED IN THE STUDENT UNION). IN ADDITION TO THIS, FOOD SERVICE ALSO OPERATES THE VENDING AND ALL THE CATERING ON CAMPUS. ALL STUDENTS RESIDING IN THE SOMERS RESIDENCE HALL ARE REQUIRED TO BE ON A MEAL PLAN, OF WHICH THERE ARE A VARIETY TO CHOOSE FROM. OPTIONAL MEAL PLANS ARE AVAILABLE FOR ALL OTHER HALL RESIDENTS AND COMMUTER STUDENTS. FOR 2009-10, THE COLLEGE HAD OVER 1,350 STUDENTS ON VARIOUS MEAL PLANS. THE STUDENT CENTER FOR HEALTH SERVICES AND WELL-BEING CONSISTS OF A PROFESSIONAL PROGRAM STAFF INCLUDING RNS, NURSE PRACTITIONERS, PHYSICAL THERAPISTS, AND MASTER'S LEVEL COUNSELORS. SERVICES PROVIDED INCLUDE: PRIMARY HEALTHCARE INCLUDING PHYSICAL EXAMS FOR ACUTE ILLNESS AND INJURY, PREVENTATIVE HEALTH CARE, AND PRESCRIPTIONS; PSYCHIATRIC EVALUATION AND MEDICATION MANAGEMENT; PHYSICAL THERAPY CONSULTATIONS; INDIVIDUAL COUNSELING TO ENHANCE GROWTH AND EMOTIONAL WELL-BEING; INFORMATION AND EDUCATION IN THE AREAS OF LIFE SKILLS, ALCOHOL AND DRUG USE AND ABUSE, LIFE TRANSITIONS, ETC.; AND COUNSELING FOR ACADEMIC SUCCESS.

Form990ScheduleCPartIV.Explanation: THE ORGANIZATION'S LOBBYING ACTIVITIES ARE LIMITED TO PROCURING FUNDING FOR THE COLLEGE RELATING TO OUR STUDENT FINANCIAL AID PROGRAM AND FOR FEDERAL AND STATE GRANTS RELATING TO THE ACADEMIC PURPOSE OF THE COLLEGE.

Form990ScheduleDPartXIV.ReturnReference: Description of How Organization Reports Conservation Easements:
Form990ScheduleDPartXIV.Explanation: THERE ARE NO REVENUES ASSOCIATED WITH THIS EASEMENT. EXPENSES FOR MONITORING FLOW THROUGH THE COLLEGE'S OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE ACCOUNT. LAND FALLING UNDER THE EASEMENT IS INCLUDED UNDER "LAND" IN THE COLLEGE'S BALANCE SHEET. THERE IS NO FOOTNOTE RELATING TO THE EASEMENT IN THE COLLEGE'S FINANCIAL STATEMENTS.

DUE TO IMMATERIALITY, THERE IS NO FOOTNOTE RELATED TO COLLECTIONS OF ART, HISTORICAL TREASURES, AND SIMILIAR ASSETS IN THE COLLEGE'S FINANCIAL STATEMENTS. THE COLLEGE'S COLLECTION (ART) CONSISTS PRIMARILY OF PICTURES AND STATUES DEPICTING SCENES AND EVENTS FROM THE HISTORY OF ST. BENEDICT AND ST. SCHOLASTICA. THE COLLEGE WAS FOUNDED IN 1912 BY THE BENEDICTINE SISTERS BENEVOLENT ASSOCIATION AND IS SHAPED BY THE BENEDICTINE HERITAGE; ARTWORK CONTRIBUTES TO THIS HERITAGE VIA PUBLIC DISPLAY IN HALLWAYS IN THE MAIN BUILDING ON CAMPUS.

THE ESCROW AMOUNT REPRESENTS FUNDS HELD BY THE COLLEGE FOR STUDENT CLUBS AND ORGANIZATIONS (I.E., COLLEGE STUDENT NEWSPAPER, STUDENT SENATE, ETC.). REPRESENTATIVES OF THESE STUDENT ORGANIZATIONS ARE ABLE TO MAKE WITHDRAWALS FROM THESE FUNDS AFTER PROVIDING SUPPORTING DOCUMENTATION FOR WITHDRAWALS.

Form990ScheduleIPartIV.Explanation: Schedule I, Part I, Line 2: ALL GRANT ACTIVITY IS REQUIRED TO MEET THE SPECIFIC STANDARDS AND STIPULATIONS OF THE GRANTOR AND OPERATE WITHIN THE ORGANIZATION'S POLICIES AND PROCEDURES. GRANT REVENUE AND EXPENDITURES ARE MONITORED AND FUNDS ARE DRAWN DOWN ON A MONTHLY BASIS. INTERNAL REPORTS AND AWARD LEVELS ARE REVIEWED PRIOR TO EACH DRAW TO DETERMINE IF CASH SHOULD BE DRAWN FOR INDIVIDUAL GRANTS. FINALLY, THE COLLEGE UNDERGOES AN ANNUAL AUDIT OF ITS FEDERAL AWARDS UNDER THE GUIDELINES OF OMB CIRCULAR A-133.

SCHEDULE I, PART II, COLUMN (H): FUNDS RECEIVED FROM THE MN DEPTARTMENT OF HEALTH FROM LEGISLATION THAT CREATED THE MERC TRUST FUND (PMAP/PGAMC DISTRIBUTION) THAT PROVIDES REMUNERATION FOR THOSE FACILITIES THAT SERVE AS CLINICAL TRAINING SITES FOR THE COLLEGE'S NURSE PRACTITIONER AND CLINICAL NURSE SPECIALIST STUDENTS DURING THE 2008-2009 ACADEMIC YEAR. THE AMOUNTS PAID FROM THE FUNDS RECEIVED FROM THE MERC LEGISLATION TO EACH ORGANIZATION LISTED IN PART II IS BASED ROUGHLY ON THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS THEY HAD AND THE LENGTH OF TIME THEY SPENT AT EACH RESPECTIVE FACILITY. TRAINING SITES MUST ALSO HAVE A CURRENT ACTIVE MEDICAL ASSISTANCE ENROLLMENT STATUS IN MINNESOTA.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, line 1
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE CONSISTS OF THE BOARD CHAIR, MARY IVES; JAMES ZASTROW; BETH STAUBER-JOHNSON; MIKE MILES; JOHN LABOSKY; SR. KATHLEEN HOFER; LARRY GOODWIN; AND SR. LOIS ECKES. THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE HAS A TWOFOLD PURPOSE: 1) IT SERVES AT THE PLEASURE OF THE BOARD AS ITS AGENT IN HELPING THE PRESIDENT TO ADDRESS BUSINESS MATTERS BETWEEN REGULAR BOARD MEETINGS; AND 2) IT ASSISTS THE CHAIRPERSON AND THE PRESIDENT IN THEIR JOINT RESPONSIBILITY TO HELP THE BOARD TO FUNCTION EFFECTIVELY AND EFFICIENTLY BY SUGGESTING BOARD MEETING AGENDA ITEMS AND PERIODICALLY ASSESSING THE QUALITY OF COMMITTEE WORK. THE COMMITTEE HAS AUTHORITY TO ACT FOR THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES ON ALL MATTERS EXCEPT THE FOLLOWING, WHICH SHALL BE RESERVED FOR THE BOARD: PRESIDENTIAL SELECTION AND TERMINATION; TRUSTEE AND BOARD OFFICER SELECTION; CHANGES IN INSTITUTIONAL MISSION AND PURPOSES; CHANGES TO THE BYLAWS, CHARTER, OR ARTICLES OF INCORPORATION; INCURRING OF CORPORATE INDEBTEDNESS IN EXCESS OF $100,000; SALE OF COLLEGE ASSETS OR TANGIBLE PROPERTY VALUED GREATER THAN $250,000; ADOPTION OF THE ANNUAL BUDGET; AND CONFERRAL OF DEGREES. IN ADDITION TO ITS AUTHORITY TO TAKE ACTION ON BUSINESS MATTERS WHICH CANNOT BE DEFERRED UNTIL THE BOARD'S NEXT SCHEDULED MEETING, THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE OVERSEES THE WORK OF BOARD COMMITTEES, THE COLLEGE'S PLANNING PROCESS OR PROGRESS ON PLANNING GOALS, THE BOARD'S RESPONSIBILITY TO SUPPORT THE PRESIDENT AND ASSESS HIS OR HER PERFORMANCE, AND REVIEW ANNUALLY THE PRESIDENT'S COMPENSATION AND CONDITIONS OF EMPLOYMENT.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, line 4
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: THE COLLEGE MADE THE FOLLOWING AMENDMENT TO THE GOVERNING DOCUMENTS: 1) AT ALL TIMES, UP TO 25% OF THE VOTING TRUSTEES SHALL BE MEMBERS OF THE BENEDICTINE SISTERS BENEVOLENT ASSOCIATION AS APPOINTED BY THE PRIORESS. IN DETERMINING THE 25%, FRACTIONS WILL BE ROUNDED UP.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, line 7a
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: THE PRESIDENT OF THE BENEDICTINE SISTERS BENEVOLENT ASSOCIATION AND THE PRESIDENT OF THE COLLEGE'S ALUMNI ASSOCIATION ARE VOTING MEMBERS OF THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES AND ARE ELECTED THROUGH THEIR RESPECTIVE ASSOCIATIONS. THE PRIORESS OF THE BENEDICTINE SISTERS BENEVOLENT ASSOCIATION APPOINTS UP TO 25% OF THE VOTING TRUSTEES.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, line 7b
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: AS SPONSOR OF THE COLLEGE, THE BENEDICTINE SISTERS BENEVOLENT ASSOCIATION HOLDS CERTAIN RESERVED POWERS, WHICH ARE EXERCISED BY ITS BOARD OF DIRECTORS. THE BENEDICTINE SISTERS BENEVOLENT ASSOCIATION RESERVES THE POWER TO WITHHOLD APPROVAL OF ANY ACTION OF THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES OF THE COLLEGE WHICH MAY, INTENTIONALLY OR UNINTENTIONALLY, CHANGE THE MISSION OR MISSION STATEMENT OF THE COLLEGE, ALTER THE REAL ESTATE HOLDINGS OF THE COLLEGE OR THOSE LANDS OR BUILDINGS LEASED TO THE COLLEGE BY THE BENEDICTINE SISTERS, CHANGE THE PROVISION IN ARTICLE IV, SECTION 1 WHICH REQUIRES UP TO 25% OF THE VOTING TRUSTEES TO BE MEMBERS OF THE BENEDICTINE SISTERS BENEVOLENT ASSOCIATION, OR WHICH MODIFIES ARTICLE XII, SECTION 6 OF THE BYLAWS (THIS PARAGRAPH IS ARTICLE XII, SECTION 6 OF THE BYLAWS). THE BENEDICTINE SISTERS BENEVOLENT ASSOCIATION ALSO RESERVES THE POWER TO WITHHOLD APPROVAL OF ANY MERGER, CONSOLIDATION OR LIQUIDATION INVOLVING THE COLLEGE.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 11
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: THE 2009 FORM 990 WAS PREPARED BY THE ASSISTANT CONTROLLER WITH SUBSEQUENT REVIEW BY THE CONTROLLER AND THE VICE PRESIDENT FOR FINANCE. THIS REVIEW CONSISTED OF ALL PARTS OF FORM 990 AND APPLICABLE SCHEDULES. THE COLLEGE'S INDEPENDENT AUDIT FIRM THEN REVIEWED THE FORM 990 DATA FOR ACCURACY AND COMPLIANCE WITH TAX LAW AND FORM INSTRUCTIONS. A DRAFT COPY OF THE FORM 990 WAS THEN PREPARED BY THE AUDIT FIRM AND WAS REVIEWED FOR ACCURACY BY THE VICE PRESIDENT OF FINANCE, CONTROLLER, AND ASSISTANT CONTROLLER. ANY CHANGES WERE COMMUNICATED TO AUDIT FIRM AND REVISED DRAFTS GENERATED AS NECESSARY. A DRAFT COPY OF THE FORM 990 WAS THEN PROVIDED TO THE COLLEGE'S AUDIT & FINANCE COMMITTEE FOR REVIEW AND RECOMMENDATION FOR APPROVAL BY THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES; THE PRESIDENT IS PART OF THIS COMMITTEE. THE BOARD WAS THEN PROVIDED WITH THE DRAFT COPY OF THE FORM 990 FOR REVIEW AND APPROVAL PRIOR TO FILING WITH THE IRS.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 12c
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: A TRUSTEE IS CONSIDERED TO HAVE A CONFLICT OF INTEREST IF (A) SUCH TRUSTEE HAS EXISTING OR POTENTIAL FINANCIAL OR OTHER INTERESTS WHICH IMPAIR OR MIGHT REASONABLY APPEAR TO IMPAIR SUCH MEMBER'S INDEPENDENT, UNBIASED JUDGEMENT IN THE DISCHARGE OF HIS OR HER RESPONSIBILITIES TO THE COLLEGE, OR (B) SUCH TRUSTEE IS AWARE THAT A MEMBER OF HIS OR HER FAMILY (WHICH FOR PURPOSES OF THIS ARTICLE SHALL BE A SPOUSE, PARENT, SIBLING, CHILD AND ANY OTHER RELATIVE) OR ANY ORGANIZATION IN WHICH SUCH TRUSTEE (OR MEMBER OF HIS OR HER FAMILY) IS AN OFFICER, DIRECTOR, EMPLOYEE, MEMBER, PARTNER, TRUSTEE, OR CONTROLLING STOCKHOLDER, HAS SUCH EXISTING OR POTENTIAL FINANCIAL OR OTHER INTERESTS. ALL TRUSTEES ARE REQUIRED TO DISCLOSE TO THE BOARD ANY POSSIBLE CONFLICT OF INTEREST AT THE EARLIEST PRACTICAL TIME. NO SUCH TRUSTEE MAY VOTE ON ANY MATTER UNDER CONSIDERATION AT A BOARD OR COMMITTEE MEETING, IN WHICH SUCH TRUSTEE HAS A CONFLICT OF INTEREST. THE MINUTES OF SUCH MEETING REFLECT THAT A DISCLOSURE WAS MADE AND THE TRUSTEE HAVING A CONFLICT OF INTEREST ABSTAINED FROM VOTING. ANY TRUSTEE WHO IS UNCERTAIN WHETHER A CONFLICT OF INTEREST MAY EXIST IN ANY MATTER MAY REQUEST THE BOARD OR COMMITTEE TO RESOLVE THE QUESTION BY MAJORITY VOTE. IN ORDER FOR THE COLLEGE TO CARRY OUT ITS MISSION AND PURPOSE, THE ACTIVITIES OF ALL EMPLOYEES ARE TO BE CONDUCTED ACCORDING TO THE HIGHEST STANDARDS OF INTEGRITY AND ETHICS; ALL EMPLOYEES ARE EXPECTED TO AVOID SITUATIONS WHICH MIGHT CONFLICT WITH THEIR RESPONSIBILITIES TO THE COLLEGE. IT IS CONTRARY TO THE COLLEGE'S POLICY FOR ANY EMPLOYEE OR MEMBER OF THE EMPLOYEE'S FAMILY TO ACCEPT GIFTS, SERVICES, DISCOUNTS, OR FAVORS FROM THOSE WITH WHOM THE COLLEGE DOES BUSINESS OR CONSIDERS DOING BUSINESS. IT IS NOT THE COLLEGE'S DESIRE TO APPEAR UNFRIENDLY OR UNSOCIABLE. ON THE OTHER HAND, IT IS THE COLLEGE'S POLICY TO AVOID ANY ACTIONS WHICH MAY THROW DOUBT UPON THE INTEGRITY OR MOTIVATION OF EMPLOYEES. NO GUIDELINES CAN BE ALL-INCLUSIVE AND THEREFORE THE RESPONSIBILITY FOR PROPER CONDUCT RESTS WITH EACH EMPLOYEE. PERSONAL INTEGRITY AND GOOD JUDGMENT ARE NECESSARY. EMPLOYEES SHOULD AVOID ANY SITUATION, BUSINESS, OR OTHER ACTIVITY WHICH IN ANY WAY COULD BE CONSTRUED AS A CONFLICT OF INTEREST WITH THEIR EMPLOYMENT AT THE COLLEGE OF ST. SCHOLASTICA. SUSPECTED, ACTUAL, OR POTENTIAL CONFLICTS OF INTEREST SHOULD BE REPORTED TO THE DIRECTOR OF HUMAN RESOURCES OR THE PRESIDENT OF THE COLLEGE, AND WILL THEN BE INVESTIGATED FAIRLY AND THOROUGHLY. INFORMATION CONCERNING SUSPECTED VIOLATIONS WILL BE TREATED CONFIDENTIALLY AND ONLY THOSE PERSONS WITH A DIRECT NEED TO KNOW THE INFORMATION WILL BE GIVEN ACCESS TO IT. AT THE APPROPRIATE TIME, THE COLLEGE WILL INFORM THE INVOLVED EMPLOYEE OF THE ALLEGATION, REVIEW THE INFORMATION DISCOVERED, AND ALLOW THE EMPLOYEE AN OPPORTUNITY TO RESPOND. IF THE ALLEGATIONS ARE CONFIRMED BY INVESTIGATION AND/OR ACKNOWLEDGED BY THE EMPLOYEE, DISCIPLINARY ACTION, UP TO AND INCLUDING TERMINATION, MAY RESULT.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 15a
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: RECRUITMENT AND RETENTION OF A WELL-QUALIFIED INDIVIDUAL INTO THE LEADERSHIP ROLE OF PRESIDENT IS VITAL TO THE SUCCESS AND GROWTH OF THE COLLEGE. TO SUPPORT THESE EFFORTS, THE COLLEGE HAS CREATED A METHODOLOGY TO DETERMINE A COMPETITIVE WAGE STRUCTURE FOR THIS POSITION. THE PRIMARY SOURCE FOR SALARY DATA IS THE ANNUAL COLLEGE AND UNIVERSITY PROFESSIONAL ASSOCIATION (CUPA) ADMINISTRATIVE COMPENSATION SALARY SURVEY. CUPA SURVEYS PROVIDE THE MOST COMPREHENSIVE INFORMATION ON HIGHER EDUCATION SALARY DATA THAN OTHER NATIONAL SURVEYS. DATA IS COLLECTED ON A VARIETY OF FACTORS THAT ENABLE THE COLLEGE TO CREATE A COMPARATOR GROUP OF COLLEGES THAT MOST RESEMBLE ST. SCHOLASTICA. TO CREATE THE COMPARATOR GROUP, THE FOLLOWING PARAMETERS HAVE BEEN SELECTED: COMPARABLE STUDENT ENROLLMENT, COMPARABLE OPERATING BUDGETS, PRIVATE RELIGIOUS AFFILIATION, MASTER'S LEVEL INSTRUCTION, AND MIDWEST LOCATION. THESE VARIABLES RESULTED IN A GROUP OF 11 INSTITUTIONS: BENEDICTINE UNIVERSITY (LISLE, IL); DOMINICAN UNIVERSITY (RIVER FOREST, IL); EDGEWOOD COLLEGE (MADISON,WI); FONTBONNE UNIVERSITY (ST. LOUIS, MO); FRANCISCAN UNIVERSITY OF STEUBENVILLE (STEUBENVILLE, OH); MALONE COLLEGE (CANTON, OH); NORTH PARK UNIVERSITY (CHICAGO, IL); ROCKHURST UNIVERSITY (KANSAS CITY, MO); UNIVERSITY OF EVANSVILLE (EVANSVILLE, IN); UNIVERSITY OF ST. FRANCIS (JOLIET, IL); AND WALSH UNIVERSITY (CANTON, OH). IN ADDITION TO COMPARING THE WAGES OF THE POSITION TO THIS SELECT GROUP, IT IS ALSO RECOGNIZED THAT ANOTHER COMPETITIVE GROUP FOR PRESIDENT IS OTHER MINNESOTA PRIVATE COLLEGES. THESE COLLEGES HAVE BEEN ADDED TO OUR COMPARATOR GROUP AND ARE AS FOLLOWS: AUGSBURG COLLEGE; BETHEL UNIVERSITY; CARLETON COLLEGE; COLLEGE OF ST. BENEDICT; COLLEGE OF ST. CATHERINE; CONCORDIA COLLEGE - MOORHEAD; CONCORDIA UNIVERSITY - ST. PAUL; CROWN COLLEGE; GUSTAVUS ADOLPHUS COLLEGE; HAMLINE UNIVERSITY; MACALESTER COLLEGE; NORTH CENTRAL UNIVERSITY; NORTHWESTERN COLLEGE; ST. JOHN'S UNIVERSITY; ST. MARY'S UNIVERSITY; ST. OLAF COLLEGE; AND UNIVERSITY OF ST. THOMAS. SALARY DATA FROM THIS GROUP OF SIMILAR HIGHER EDUCATION INSTITUTIONS PROVIDE SOLID COMPENSATION FIGURES THAT ARE EQUITABLE AND COMPETITIVE FOR OUR INDUSTRY WITHIN THE REGION. THE MEDIAN OF THE RANGE OF SALARIES FOR PRESIDENT OF THE LISTED INSTITUTIONS BECOMES THE MIDPOINT OR TARGET WAGE OF THE POSITION. THE COLLEGE HAS CHOSEN TO ADJUST THE MEDIAN UPWARDS BY AN ADDITIONAL 4% TO ACCOUNT FOR THE LEADERSHIP DEMANDS OF MULTIPLE CAMPUSES. THE 4% FIGURE IS DERIVED FROM CALCULATING THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN WAGES FOR SINGLE SITE INSTITUTIONS VERSUS THOSE WITH MULTIPLE SITES. ALTHOUGH CUPA IS THE PRIMARY SOURCE FOR SALARY DATA, THE COLLEGE ALSO CHECKS OTHER WAGE RELATED DATA ON AN ANNUAL BASIS TO ENSURE WAGE STRUCTURES ARE BUILT ON SOUND ECONOMIC PRINCIPLES AND REFLECT CURRENT COMPENSATION TRENDS. SPECIFIC WAGE DATA IS PRESENTED TO THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE OF THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES BY THE VICE PRESIDENT FOR HUMAN RESOURCES IN THE FALL OF EACH YEAR. THIS COMMITTEE REVIEWS THE PRESIDENT'S PERFORMANCE OVER THE PREVIOUS FISCAL YEAR AND PREPARES A SALARY RECOMMENDATION FOR FULL BOARD APPROVAL AT ITS ANNUAL OCTOBER MEETING. THE PRESIDENT'S NEW WAGE GOES INTO EFFECT THE FOLLOWING JANUARY 1. THIS PROCESS WAS LAST CONDUCTED IN 2009 FOR THE PRESIDENT, DR. GEORGE GOODWIN.
